{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a96aefcd-5a66-497a-bca3-89be9e29245b","content":"I found **3 evaluation performance anti-patterns** in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:\n\n---\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (line 13)\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\n`File::ReadAllText` runs during **evaluation**, not build execution. This blocks the MSBuild evaluator with synchronous disk I/O. **Fix:** Read the file in a target with `Inputs/Outputs` instead, or use `ReadLinesFromFile` task at build time.\n\n### 2. Expensive Wildcard Glob (line 9)\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` walks the **entire directory tree** at evaluation time. In repos with deep hierarchies (e.g., `node_modules`, `.git`), this is extremely slow. **Fix:** Narrow the glob to specific extensions/paths, or add costly directories to `DefaultItemExcludes`.\n\n### 3. Chained Import Depth (lines 6 → level1 → level2 → level3)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of nested imports. Currently small, but this pattern scales poorly—each import adds an evaluation phase pass. Keep import chains shallow and flatten where possible.\n\n---\n\n**Priority:** Issue #1 (file I/O) and #2 (deep glob) are the most impactful. The import chain is minor at 3 levels but worth watching as the project grows.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"84e0f10c-4177-489a-9b3e-b543f0d567c5","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"Now I have a good picture of the project. Let me analyze the evaluation performance issues.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"D80B:21008B:421093:4B32C9:6A03D37A"},"id":"3eeace21-6861-4bb0-9e55-ddd8ac3806ad","timestamp":"2026-05-13T01:27:34.095Z","parentId":"91f3e829-09c5-4523-92c1-a82199ffed10"}
